# Question 1

## Prompt for Question 1

-   In Step 1, you have seen how to create a summary table and modify it for various statistical analyses through recorded lecture.
-   Summarize the package's capabilities as explained by the speaker.
-   How may the {gtsummary} benefit you for your school work or career?

::: aside
Note: The recorded lecture is about "Summarizing Modeling Outputs in Publishable Tables {gtsummary}".Refer to the [lecture note](https://jmjung.quarto.pub/publishable-summary-table-with-gtsummary/) provided by Dr. Jung.
:::

## Answer for Question 1

-   There are numerous great features available from the gtsummary package in R.
-   Gtsummary provides a flexible, high-quality, and visually appealing way to make a summary table for various statistical analyses.
-   It is customizable and can be utilized for any publication, such as a thesis or research paper.

## Answer for Question 1 (Continued)

**Key Capabilities - gtsummary package**

::: {.medium-small .incremental}
**1. Make a summary table automatically**

-   Based on the variable type (continuous or categorical) you have, the package automatically chooses the appropriate statistical method/test, for example, the Chi-square test and t-test.

**2. Highly customizable and easy to format**

-   You can easily customize the appearance and details of the tables based on your preference. Users can format p-values, confidence intervals, change decimal places for precision, and include additional features in tables such as footnotes and headers.

**3. Support various data types**

-   The package supports a variety of statistical scenarios, for example, cross-tabulation, multiple regression, logistic regression, ANCOVA, experimental design, and analysis for survey data.
-   The package will show output clearly and concisely since it gives functions especially tailored for statistical tests.

**4. Easily integrate with other packages available in R**

-   The gtsummary package integrates easily and smoothly with many other packages available in R, for example, gt package.
-   Users can utilize this capability in order to improve and further customize the summary table.
:::

## Answer for Question 1 (Continued)

**Benefits for School/Professional Work with the gtsummary package**

-   The gtsummary package will benefit my school work, especially for the culminating project we are currently working on.
-   Since the culminating project involves data analysis, I can utilize all the capabilities of the package in my project.
-   For a part of the data analysis, I will use logistic regression. I can use the package in order to simplify the steps of producing clear and reproducible summary tables which can be used for both the written report and presentation.
-   The package capabilities of displaying the complex statistical results in an easy-to-understand and navigate format/table will help me to present the key findings clearly and improve the overall quality of any data analysis work.

# Question 2

## Prompt for Question 2

-   In Step 2, you watched [YouTube Video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tANo9E1SYJE), the extended presentation of the {gtsummary} package by Dr. Daniel Dsjoberg, the very creator of the gtsummary package.
-   Q2.1: How does gtsummary differ from gt and gtExtras?
-   Q2.2: Give three things you learned newly that were not explained in the lecture in Step 1/Question 1.

::: aside
Note: Refer to the [YouTube Video by Dr. Daniel Dsjoberg](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tANo9E1SYJE) and his [lecture slides](https://www.danieldsjoberg.com/gtsummary-weill-cornell-presentation/#1).
:::

## Answer for Question 2.1

-   Gt, gtExtras, and gtsummary packages in R are different from each other but have the purpose of complementing each other in terms of table creation and customization.

1.  **gt** package functions as the foundational tools to produce and customize the table along with features like headers, footers and cell format.

2.  **gtExtras** package contains advanced/extended capabilities of gt packages and allows users to improve and simplify further for visualization process.

3.  **gtsummary** package is ideal for data and statistic analysis since it specializes in creating reproducible summary tables based on the analysis insight, which are ready to use for any publication.

## Answer for Question 2.2

**Three features I learned about gtsummary from [Dr.Dsjober's video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tANo9E1SYJE)**

::: {.medium-small .incremental}
**1. Seamless integration with various output formats**

-   Tables created with gtsummary packages can be rendered into different types of output formats, such as HTML, PDF, and Word. This feature allows users to smoothly apply the table into their preferred file types for your paper, report, and documents.

**2. Customize through themes**

-   gtsummary has theme capabilities, which allow users to have a default theme and options for tables. This capability will help users to eliminate repetitive tasks when coding the table appearance and customization.
-   Some of the themes available from the package already align perfectly with the published guidelines from certain journals.
-   E.g.the theme_gtsummary_journal(journal = "jama") already aligns with the Journal of the American Media Association’s guidelines.

**3. Inline text report**

-   The package can extract statistics from tables and directly incorporate the statistics and analysis results into the text of a report.
-   This capability eliminates the extra steps of producing separate tables or charts and makes it easy to update the report even if there are changes in the original data or analysis.
-   This helps to create a seamless and readable flow of data insight and information within the report and offers easier understanding of the data for the audience.
:::

# Question 3

## Prompt for Question 3

-   Apply what you learned to your MSDM CEP data. Choose two appropriate variables for cross-tabulation and show if the two variables are associated or not.
-   Use appropriate statistics to test if the two variables are associated.
-   Provide Code, produce the table, and interpret the result.

## Answer for Question 3

-   I used **Chi-square test** for Variable 1: Customer satisfaction (binary: Satisfied or Neutral/Dissatisfied) & Variable 2: Travel type (Business travel or personal travel).



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true" code-summary="Expand for full code"}
library(gtsummary)
library(readxl)
library(dplyr)

data <- read_excel("Satisfaction.xlsx")

data <- data %>%
  mutate(
    Satisfaction = factor(Satisfaction, levels = c(0, 1), labels = c("Neutral/Dissatisfied", "Satisfied")),
    TravelType = as.factor(TravelType)
  )

table_result <- tbl_cross(
  data = data,
  row = TravelType,
  col = Satisfaction,
  percent = "row"
) %>%
  add_p(test = "chisq.test") 

table_result
```

